# HTML Report Layout

The generated HTML report must include these sections **in this order**:

1. `#report-header` — title, generation timestamp, date range covered
2. `#kpi-cards` — Total MRR, Total Customers, Churn Rate (%), Average Revenue Per Customer
3. `#mrr-trend` — line chart, MRR by month
4. `#revenue-by-plan` — bar or donut chart, MRR by plan tier
5. `#churn-analysis` — monthly churn trend (line chart or table)
6. `#top-customers` — table sorted by MRR: company, plan, MRR, signup date, activity level
7. `#engagement-summary` — event counts by type (bar chart or table)

## HTML requirements

- Use `<section id="...">` for each block above
- Output must be a single self-contained HTML file
- KPI values must come from SQL queries, not hardcoded placeholders
- Charts may use inline SVG or an embedded chart library; avoid requiring a separate build step
- Top customers table must show exactly up to 10 rows, sorted by MRR descending

## report_generator.py conventions

- Accept `--output` CLI argument (default: `report.html`)
- Read from `database.db` in the project root (or accept `--db-path`)
- No LLM or external AI API calls at runtime
- Separate data queries from HTML rendering where practical
